Tomorrow marks the 73rd anniversary of the liberation of Auschwitz-Birkenau, the Nazi death and concentration camp in Nazi-occupied Poland. This article highlights the importance of remembering the Holocaust and the systematic persecution and murder of six million Jewish people by the Nazis. It also recognizes that the Nazis enslaved and killed millions of other groups, including Slavs, Roma, gays, people with disabilities, priests, religious leaders, and others who opposed their regime. The article emphasizes the debt owed to Holocaust survivors, who continue to educate society about their experiences and promote respect for human rights. It calls for every generation to learn from the Holocaust and work towards preventing new horrors against humanity. The article concludes by pledging to stamp out prejudice, condemn hatred, and protect the rights and dignity of every human being.